<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="135" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1122,2013]" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1374,1400]" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Female subgenital plate short, transverse, truncated posteriorly, occupies anterior half of the sternum 8; unevenly pigmented, anterolateral edges pale, posterior margin straight or slightly rounded medially, and strongly sclerotized; inner sclerite of vaginal complex small, tooth-shaped, and black. Two or three thin transverse shallow membranous folds and a pair of lateral sclerites located below posterolateral margin the subgenital plate. Genital opening of the vaginal complex is broad.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="138" pageId="2" pageNumber="135" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1122,2013]" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1554,1580]" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">Description</emphasis>
. Medium-sized species, body length 
<quantity box="[774,913,1554,1581]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.7" metricValueMax="6.2" metricValueMin="5.2" pageId="2" pageNumber="135" unit="mm" value="5.7" valueMax="6.2" valueMin="5.2">5.2–6.2 mm</quantity>
(n=7), darkly sclerotized, and overall brown color (
<figureCitation box="[224,302,1591,1617]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1879,1903]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,594,1853]" captionTargetId="figure-212@3.[151,1436,594,1853]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Female of Capnia yavorskayae sp. nov. Paratype. 1. Habitus, dorsal. 2. Right forewing. 3. Right hindwing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669362" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669362/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[316,362,1591,1618]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–7" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1895,1919]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-30@4.[151,1435,181,1871]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4–7. Female of Capnia yavorskayae sp. nov. Paratype. 4. Mesothoracic sclerite, ventral: Bs—basisternum; Fs— furcasternum; Fsa—furcasternal arm; Fsp—furcasternal pit; Kes—katepisternum; Pfs—postfurcasternum; Prs—presternum; PPfs—prothoracic postfurcasternum; Sc—spinasternum; Tn—trochantin. 5–6. Abdominal tip, variation of the subgenital plate. 7. Vaginal complex (cleared) with genital opening, membranous genital cavity, inner tooth-shaped black sclerite." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669364" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669364/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">4–6</figureCitation>
). Setation is dense and long, especially on abdomen and cerci (
<figureCitation box="[1072,1149,1591,1617]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1879,1903]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,594,1853]" captionTargetId="figure-212@3.[151,1436,594,1853]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Female of Capnia yavorskayae sp. nov. Paratype. 1. Habitus, dorsal. 2. Right forewing. 3. Right hindwing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669362" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669362/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">Figs. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1164,1210,1591,1618]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–7" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1895,1919]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-30@4.[151,1435,181,1871]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4–7. Female of Capnia yavorskayae sp. nov. Paratype. 4. Mesothoracic sclerite, ventral: Bs—basisternum; Fs— furcasternum; Fsa—furcasternal arm; Fsp—furcasternal pit; Kes—katepisternum; Pfs—postfurcasternum; Prs—presternum; PPfs—prothoracic postfurcasternum; Sc—spinasternum; Tn—trochantin. 5–6. Abdominal tip, variation of the subgenital plate. 7. Vaginal complex (cleared) with genital opening, membranous genital cavity, inner tooth-shaped black sclerite." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669364" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669364/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">4–6</figureCitation>
). Antenna is moderately long, with 31 or more segments. Cercus slender and hairy, shorter than the abdomen length, with 11 or more club-shaped segments; third basal segment as long as wide, further ones are gradually elongated (
<figureCitation box="[1240,1347,1662,1690]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–7" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1895,1919]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-30@4.[151,1435,181,1871]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4–7. Female of Capnia yavorskayae sp. nov. Paratype. 4. Mesothoracic sclerite, ventral: Bs—basisternum; Fs— furcasternum; Fsa—furcasternal arm; Fsp—furcasternal pit; Kes—katepisternum; Pfs—postfurcasternum; Prs—presternum; PPfs—prothoracic postfurcasternum; Sc—spinasternum; Tn—trochantin. 5–6. Abdominal tip, variation of the subgenital plate. 7. Vaginal complex (cleared) with genital opening, membranous genital cavity, inner tooth-shaped black sclerite." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669364" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669364/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">Figs. 5, 6</figureCitation>
); apical cercal segments are the longest with their length about three times of their width, intercalary setae are dense and short (
<figureCitation box="[223,288,1735,1761]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1879,1903]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,594,1853]" captionTargetId="figure-212@3.[151,1436,594,1853]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Female of Capnia yavorskayae sp. nov. Paratype. 1. Habitus, dorsal. 2. Right forewing. 3. Right hindwing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669362" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669362/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1122,2013]" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">
Wings shortened, forewing length 
<quantity box="[584,720,1771,1797]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.449999999999999" metricValueMax="4.6" metricValueMin="4.3" pageId="2" pageNumber="135" unit="mm" value="4.449999999999999" valueMax="4.6" valueMin="4.3">
4.3 
<emphasis box="[619,633,1771,1796]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">–</emphasis>
4.6 mm
</quantity>
, wingspan 
<quantity box="[845,996,1771,1797]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.899999999999999" metricValueMax="10.2" metricValueMin="9.6" pageId="2" pageNumber="135" unit="mm" value="9.899999999999999" valueMax="10.2" valueMin="9.6">9.6‒10.2 mm</quantity>
; brownish along radial field, veins dark brown, margins with relatively long brown bristles (
<figureCitation box="[732,838,1807,1833]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1879,1903]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,594,1853]" captionTargetId="figure-212@3.[151,1436,594,1853]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Female of Capnia yavorskayae sp. nov. Paratype. 1. Habitus, dorsal. 2. Right forewing. 3. Right hindwing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669362" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669362/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">Figs. 2, 3</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis box="[859,884,1807,1839]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">
R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[876,884,1825,1839]" fontSize="6" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">1</subScript>
</emphasis>
of forewing typical of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pictet" authorityYear="1841" box="[1141,1223,1807,1833]" class="Insecta" family="Capniidae" genus="Capnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="135" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1141,1223,1807,1833]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">Capnia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, bent upward at its origin, four cross veins between 
<emphasis box="[518,537,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">C</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[592,618,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">Sc</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[633,661,1843,1868]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">Rs</emphasis>
bears two apical branches, two veins between 
<emphasis box="[1189,1212,1843,1868]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">М</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[1267,1308,1843,1875]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">
Cu 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1300,1308,1861,1875]" fontSize="6" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">2</subScript>
</emphasis>
; anal veins two (
<figureCitation box="[209,278,1879,1905]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1879,1903]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,594,1853]" captionTargetId="figure-212@3.[151,1436,594,1853]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Female of Capnia yavorskayae sp. nov. Paratype. 1. Habitus, dorsal. 2. Right forewing. 3. Right hindwing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669362" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669362/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Hindwing paler than forewing, veins brownish (
<figureCitation box="[836,904,1879,1905]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1879,1903]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,594,1853]" captionTargetId="figure-212@3.[151,1436,594,1853]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. Female of Capnia yavorskayae sp. nov. Paratype. 1. Habitus, dorsal. 2. Right forewing. 3. Right hindwing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669362" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669362/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1122,2013]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1437,151,573]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="136" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">
Mesothoracic sclerite (
<figureCitation box="[454,522,1915,1941]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–7" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1895,1919]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-30@4.[151,1435,181,1871]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4–7. Female of Capnia yavorskayae sp. nov. Paratype. 4. Mesothoracic sclerite, ventral: Bs—basisternum; Fs— furcasternum; Fsa—furcasternal arm; Fsp—furcasternal pit; Kes—katepisternum; Pfs—postfurcasternum; Prs—presternum; PPfs—prothoracic postfurcasternum; Sc—spinasternum; Tn—trochantin. 5–6. Abdominal tip, variation of the subgenital plate. 7. Vaginal complex (cleared) with genital opening, membranous genital cavity, inner tooth-shaped black sclerite." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669364" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669364/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="135">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
) from ventral view features narrow spinasternum (Sс), not fused with prothoracic postfurcasternum (PPfs) and large basisternum (Bs); median-sized subtriangular presternum (Prs) not fused with basisternum; subtriangular furcasternum (Fs) fused with basisternum, furcasternal arms (Fsa), and furcasternal pit (Fsp); postfurcasternum (Pfs) divided into two lateral, suboval sclerites not fused with others; katepisternum (Kes) separated from basisternum and trochantin (Tn).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="3" pageNumber="136">
Abdominal terga 1−8 brown with broad longitudinal membranous areas along the midline, integument light, matte in appearance. Terga 9‒10 are fully sclerotized. Abdominal sterna 1 
<emphasis box="[988,1002,259,284]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="136">–</emphasis>
7 with paired unsclerotized paralateral bands, sternum 7 slightly longer than others (
<figureCitation box="[649,754,294,322]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–7" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1895,1919]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-30@4.[151,1435,181,1871]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4–7. Female of Capnia yavorskayae sp. nov. Paratype. 4. Mesothoracic sclerite, ventral: Bs—basisternum; Fs— furcasternum; Fsa—furcasternal arm; Fsp—furcasternal pit; Kes—katepisternum; Pfs—postfurcasternum; Prs—presternum; PPfs—prothoracic postfurcasternum; Sc—spinasternum; Tn—trochantin. 5–6. Abdominal tip, variation of the subgenital plate. 7. Vaginal complex (cleared) with genital opening, membranous genital cavity, inner tooth-shaped black sclerite." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669364" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669364/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="136">Figs. 5, 6</figureCitation>
). Sternum 8 has a short, transverse subgenital plate, truncated posteriorly, length does not exceed ½ the length of the sternum 8 (
<figureCitation box="[912,1023,330,358]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–7" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1895,1919]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-30@4.[151,1435,181,1871]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4–7. Female of Capnia yavorskayae sp. nov. Paratype. 4. Mesothoracic sclerite, ventral: Bs—basisternum; Fs— furcasternum; Fsa—furcasternal arm; Fsp—furcasternal pit; Kes—katepisternum; Pfs—postfurcasternum; Prs—presternum; PPfs—prothoracic postfurcasternum; Sc—spinasternum; Tn—trochantin. 5–6. Abdominal tip, variation of the subgenital plate. 7. Vaginal complex (cleared) with genital opening, membranous genital cavity, inner tooth-shaped black sclerite." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669364" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669364/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="136">Figs. 5, 6</figureCitation>
). An oval, unevenly pigmented spot occupies most of the subgenital plate, with pale anterolateral edges. Posterior margin strongly sclerotized, straight or slightly rounded medially, covered posterolaterally with long setae, and overlapping a small tooth-shaped black inner sclerite (
<figureCitation box="[312,419,438,466]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–7" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1895,1919]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-30@4.[151,1435,181,1871]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4–7. Female of Capnia yavorskayae sp. nov. Paratype. 4. Mesothoracic sclerite, ventral: Bs—basisternum; Fs— furcasternum; Fsa—furcasternal arm; Fsp—furcasternal pit; Kes—katepisternum; Pfs—postfurcasternum; Prs—presternum; PPfs—prothoracic postfurcasternum; Sc—spinasternum; Tn—trochantin. 5–6. Abdominal tip, variation of the subgenital plate. 7. Vaginal complex (cleared) with genital opening, membranous genital cavity, inner tooth-shaped black sclerite." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669364" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669364/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="136">Figs. 5, 6</figureCitation>
). Two or three thin transverse shallow membranous folds are below the subgenital plate. A pair of lateral sclerites located below posterolateral margins of subgenital plate at the membranous half of sternum 8 and do not exceed the length of sternum (
<figureCitation box="[644,754,510,538]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–7" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1895,1919]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-30@4.[151,1435,181,1871]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4–7. Female of Capnia yavorskayae sp. nov. Paratype. 4. Mesothoracic sclerite, ventral: Bs—basisternum; Fs— furcasternum; Fsa—furcasternal arm; Fsp—furcasternal pit; Kes—katepisternum; Pfs—postfurcasternum; Prs—presternum; PPfs—prothoracic postfurcasternum; Sc—spinasternum; Tn—trochantin. 5–6. Abdominal tip, variation of the subgenital plate. 7. Vaginal complex (cleared) with genital opening, membranous genital cavity, inner tooth-shaped black sclerite." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669364" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669364/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="136">Figs. 5, 6</figureCitation>
). Vaginal complex with broad genital opening, membranous genital cavity reaches the middle of the segment 7 where it branches into the oviducts (
<figureCitation box="[1126,1194,547,573]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–7" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1895,1919]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-30@4.[151,1435,181,1871]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 4–7. Female of Capnia yavorskayae sp. nov. Paratype. 4. Mesothoracic sclerite, ventral: Bs—basisternum; Fs— furcasternum; Fsa—furcasternal arm; Fsp—furcasternal pit; Kes—katepisternum; Pfs—postfurcasternum; Prs—presternum; PPfs—prothoracic postfurcasternum; Sc—spinasternum; Tn—trochantin. 5–6. Abdominal tip, variation of the subgenital plate. 7. Vaginal complex (cleared) with genital opening, membranous genital cavity, inner tooth-shaped black sclerite." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6669364" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6669364/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="136">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
